<p>On Saturday, February 8, 1958, at the Newark City Hospital (Harrison S. Martland Medical Center), in the early morning hours of that cold but sunny day, Charles and Doris Walton were blessed with the birth of their only son, Ricardo.  He is one of seven children, six (6) girls and one (1) male child.</p>

<p>Ricardo received his primary and secondary education through the City of Newark Public School system; he attended Robert Treat Elementary School from kindergarten through 5th grade.  As a result of the construction of the New Jersey College of Medicine and Dentistry and the devastation caused by the 1967 riots, the family was forced to relocate from 95 Hunterdon Street, Newark Central Ward (or 3rd Ward) to 77 Summit Ave, Newark South Ward. Ricardo completed his primary education at Chancellor Avenue Elementary School in 1972; he went on to attend Weequahic High School and graduated in 1976.</p>

<p>Post secondary education consisted of three years at Mercer County Community College (MCCC), one and a half years as a full time student and one and a half years as a part time student, earning and receiving an Associate in Applied Science (A.A.S.) Degree in Civil Engineering Technology, May 1979. Not satisfied with the A.A.S. Degree, Ricardo continued his education at the New Jersey Institute of Technology (NJIT), graduating in May 1984 (December 1983) with a Bachelors’ of Science in Engineering Technology. It must be noted that he did not burden his parents or take out a loan for college; he worked and eventually managed Dawson’s Hardware Store, located in the South Ward of Newark, and did small home repairs to pay for his post secondary education. It also must be noted that the hardware store was owned by his uncle, Augustus Dawson.</p>

<p>During a road trip to the Southern States to visit family with his mother, celebrating his graduation from MCCC, Ricardo had an epiphany, he realized that he was in love with and missed his then girlfriend, Versie M. Cotten. He called her that evening and professed his love for her and asked that she marry him. Not setting a date, but promising that after he graduates and can provide for a family he would make her his wife. On August 5, 1984 his dream came true and Versie became his wife, and from that union was born three children, Halim Ibn McNeil (married to Ryan), Nicole Aisha McNeil, and Justin Charles W. McNeil.  In addition, Ricardo and Versie are blessed to have three grand children, Zahir H. McNeil, Rian Crawford and Miliah McNeil. His three children has made him very proud, first because of the love that they have for each other, secondly , they all completed  post secondary education (on his dime), and lastly for the God fearing adults that they have become. </p>

<p>Ricardo is employed by the New Jersey Turnpike Authority (NJTA) in the Engineering Department as a Project Engineer. Over the course of his 16 years with the NJTA, Ricardo has successfully managed construction contracts in an aggregate amount of well over three quarters of a billion dollars. In 2005 and 2007, during Public Service Recognition Week, at the New Jersey Excellence through Public Service Awards Programs, he received an Exceptional Service Award and Professional Achievement Award, respectively, for the success of the projects that he was directly responsible for during the periods covered. Ricardo believes that his work ethic and professionalism is the by-product of the 12 years that he spent as a Resident Engineer, with The RBA Group, a Civil / Architectural Firm and the several years he spent in the City of Newark as a Construction Specialist, administering Community Development Block Grant Funds through an array of Neighborhood Improvement programs implemented by the City. Also, the years of service to the South Ward and surrounding communities while employed at Dawson’s Hardware can never be discounted when considering the major experiences that have shaped Ricardo into the service minded person that he is today. He has held some form of employment since his early childhood, starting by delivering the Newark Star Ledger before going to school and the Newark Evening News after school, hard work has never been a stranger to Ricardo.</p> 

<p>Ricardo and his family are members of Saint Matthew AME Church, Orange New Jersey. While attending a mandatory God-Parenting Ministry Class at Saint Matthew and attending the Christening of His God Daughter, Taylor White, the Spirit of the Lord knocked on his heart. He continued to visit Saint Matthew several more times with his family and unknown to them at the time,  he decided to take that leap of faith and carried his wife and three children with him down the aisle to give the Pastor his hand, but more importantly, giving God his Heart. That bright sunny June morning in 1995 was the start of a new beginning for the McNeil Family.</p>

<p>Ricardo is a sports activist; you name it he played it, baseball, softball, basketball, football, racquetball, and paddleball and as recent, golf. He has served as a baseball coach for Irvington P.A.L., President and Captain of the Newark Paddleball Alliance, Paddleball instructor for the Newark Paddleball Academy, and has served on an Advisory Board (early 1980s) for the Newark Hawthorn Avenue Boys Club; Ricardo has always given 110% to anything that he becomes a part of.</p> 

<p>The experiences of Ricardo’s life have forged him into the man that he has become.  In December, 1997 he picked up the implements of Speculative Masonry at Golden Rule Lodge No. 24, Vauxhall, NJ by being initiated into the Great Fraternity of Free and Accepted Masons, Prince Hall Affiliated. The implements of masonry are now being applied where needed to complete his structure. In June 2009, Ricardo was elected as the Junior Grand Warden which started his journey toward the Grand East. On June 25, 2013, Ricardo was bestowed the distinguished Honor of being Elected and Installed as the Eighty Seventh (87th)   Grand Master of the Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge, Free and Accepted Masons State of New Jersey.  It is hoped and prayed that God will continue to smile upon and bless him to freely give of himself, making his motto come to life “We are our Brothers Keeper, and by so doing, he may inspire others to do the same.<p>

