$oziel = "<p style='text-align:center'>
There’s a sweet, sweet Spirit in this place<br>
And I know that it’s the Spirit of the Lord <br>
There are sweet expressions on each face<br> 
And I know they feel the presence of the Lord <br>
Sweet Holy Spirit... sweet heavenly dove...<br> 
Stay right here with us Filling us with Your love<br> 
And for these blessings <br>
We lift our hearts in praise <br>
Without a doubt we’ll know<br> 
That we have been revived <br>
When we shall leave this place
</p>

<p>First giving all honor our praise to the ever living and true God, who brought us to this today, and if that wasn’t enough, think about His Grace and Mercy that has carried Oziel Grand Chapter over the last one hundred years, I don’t know about you but I can’t help but say Thank You Lord.</p>

<p>To Sister Janice E. Justice, Centennial Grand Worthy Matron, to Brother Cecil Allen, Centennial Grand Worthy Patron, to the Elected Grand Chapter Officers, Past Grand Worthy Matrons and Patrons, Visiting Grand Jurisdictions, Certainly to the Grand Chapter of New Jersey, who for the first time is seated in our session, to the Worthy Matrons, Worthy Patrons, Chapter offices, sisters and brothers, good morning.</p>

<p>I bring you greetings on behalf of my office as the eighty seventh (87) Grand Master of the Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge, Free and Accepted Masons, State of New Jersey.</p>

<p>One Hundred years of existence is a major milestone for any organization, and should be celebrated. During the last one hundred years there were a number of monumental moments that have affected our life’s; in the first twenty five (25) years, 1913 to 1938, the Harlem Renaissance was born, which marked an era in black literature and art, the second twenty five (25) years, 1938-1963, President Franklin D. Roosevelt issued an executive order forbidding discrimination in defense industries after pressure from blacks led by A. Philip Randolph; In Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas, the Supreme Court completed overturning legal school segregation at all levels; Congress passed the voting rights bill of 1957, the first major civil rights legislation in more than 75 years; in the third twenty five (25) years, 1963-1988, Guion (Guy) S. Bluford, Jr. was the first black American astronaut to make a space flight on board the space shuttle Challenger, Shirley Chisholm became the first black congresswoman and began the first of seven terms, Barbara Jordan represented Texas in the U.S. House of Representatives from 1972-78 and was the first African-American congresswoman from the Deep South; in the last twenty five (25) years, 1988-2013, Barack Hussein Obama II, is elected the 44th and current President of the United States, the first African American to hold the office, Janice E. Justice and Cecil Allen elected as Grand Worthy Matron and Grand Worthy Patron, respectively, of the Oziel Grand Chapter Order of the Eastern Star, Prince Hall Affiliation, State of New Jersey. If you think the last one hundred years was amazing, wait to you get a load of the next one Hundred, the best is yet to come, provided that we follow the Will and Guidance of He who has directed the path of our ancestors and have brought us thus far.</p>

<p>Yesterday as I delivered my acceptance address, I could barely hold back the tears, my heart and mind was filled with memories of moments and people in my life who through Gods divine intervention shaped the man that you see in front of you today. I know that I am standing on the shoulders of some giants and I’m grateful. It is my humble prayer that God would continue to bless me with a humble heart and all that I do would first be to his Honor and Glory and then for the betterment of the craft at large. It will be my practice to make all decision based on the facts presented or known at the time, in compliance with the book of Constitution and Bylaws adopted by this August body and what’s best for the craft.</p>

<p>You have heard that my Scripture comes from Matthew 25:40 “And the King will answer and say to them, assuredly, I say to you, inasmuch as you did it to one of the least of these My brethren, you did it to Me.”</p>

<p>You have heard that my Motto is “We are our Brother’s Keeper”. Every day is filled with test, and remember, how you respond to the test will determine whether or not you hear those words “Come, you blessed of My Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world”, chose wisely when determining whether or not you will partake of the superfluities of life or help your fellow man.</p>

<p><b>The Craft is expected to complete the following program over the next year:</b><br>

 - Church Visitation, continue to nurture and reinforce relationships with the neighboring houses of worship by supporting their programs and ministries as much as possible. <br><br>

 - Black History Program during the month of February, but also throughout the year, when ever speaking in public, take a moment to discuss prominent Prince Hall Masons and their contributions where appropriate.<br><br>

 - Community involvement – Adopt a school, participate in Community programs, open the doors of the lodges to Community Groups, partner with the various civic organizations in your communities, Promote Prince Hall Masonry outside the oblong square and on the streets of your community by organizing drives as needed. <br><br>

 - Outreach to the Widows, Orphans and the sick and distress <br><br>

 - District Wide programs – Bringing awareness to Autistic Black Children and Epilepsy in the Black community.<br></p>

<p>It is my desire that the entire Prince Hall family in the respective Districts support the endeavors of their foundation Lodges. Keeping in mind that the Lodge is in fact the foundation upon which they are erected, and the lodge is the only source of their new membership, so if the Lodges waste away and reduced to rubble, so will they.</p>

<p>As I look out across this room, there is no doubt that we are one family and are bound by the lessons in Masonic virtues exhibited by the five star points:<br>
<b>Adah</b>, Jephthah’s daughter demonstrates respect to the binding force of a vow <br>
<b>Ruth</b>, the widow demonstrates devotion to religious principles<br> 
<b>Esther</b>, the wife demonstrates fidelity to kindred and friends<br> 
<b>Martha</b>, Lazarus’s sister demonstrates undeviating faith in the hour of trial<br> 
<b>Electa</b>, the mother, friend of St. John, demonstrates patience and submission under wrong</p>

<p>Before I take my seat, I will leave these thoughts with you: Live like God will deliver you Live like he works to protect you from harm Cry out to him and put your hardships on display before the Lord Remember, crisis does not come to your life only to steal and cause pain, it is also a birthplace of the miraculous</p>"; 

$charge = "<p>Worshipful Brothers, you have been chosen to be the leaders of your respective lodges, and as such you have obviously throughout your Masonic career demonstrated some leadership traits that have convinced the craft to follow you. The five leadership traits that I believe you have demonstrated are Honesty, Forward-Looking, Competency Inspiration and Intelligence.</p>

<p>It is important to continue to exhibit, model and display these traits throughout your administrative year. It isn’t enough to just be neutral. Sometimes you will have to make a tough unpopular decision; that decision should be based on the facts in front of you in collaboration with three invaluable resources, the Holy Bible, The Grand Lodge Book of Constitution and by-laws, particularly Chapter III, Laws Pertaining to the Lodges, and the By-Laws of your respective lodges. Remember never to preside in an arbitrary (random) or unconstitutional manner.</p>

<p>You will provide to me, by September 1, 2013 the required letter indicating that you have read or had read to you the Book of Constitution (see section 139). This is also required from your Wardens under separate cover.</p>

<p>You are expected to support the programs of this Grand Lodge and see that the implementation of the mandatory programs is carried out in your respective lodges.</p>

<p>Remember to always give some form of light (lecture) at every meeting.</p>

<p>As I dismiss you, I will leave you with the words of our Progenitor, MW Prince Hall</p>

<p>“We by the grace of God, live up to our profession; we may cheerfully go the rounds of the compass of this life, having lived according to the plumb line of uprightness, the square of justice, the level of truth and sincerity. And when we are come to the end of time, we may then bid farewell to that delightful Sun and Moon, and the other planets, that move so beautifully round her in their orbits, and all things here below, and ascend to that new Jerusalem, where we shall not want these tapers, for God is the Light thereof; where the Wicked cease from troubling, and where the weary are at rest.</p>

<p style='text-align:center'>
Then shall we hear and see and know,<br>
All we desired and wished below,<br>
And every power find sweet employ,<br>
In that eternal world of Joy.<br>
Our flesh shall slumber in the ground,<br>
Till the last trumpet’s joyful sound,<br>
Then burst the chains with sweet surprise,<br>
And in our Savior’s image rise.<br>
Go in Peace my Brothers and be leaders of men.</p>";
